  "summary": "Hercule Poirot meets Michael Garfield in an underground garden, where Poirot praises the aesthetic beauty of the location. During their conversation, Poirot notes that Ariadne Oliver, a best-selling author, helped bring him to the area. Poirot mentions that apples from a Halloween evening party brought him there and remarks that attending a murder party is an unpleasant experience. When discussing a child named Joyce, Garfield dismisses her as insignificant and boring. Poirot concludes the conversation by noting that murders are typically motivated by interests, fears, or love.\n\nAfter Poirot departs, he is met by a twelve-year-old girl named Miranda, who is waiting to escort him to tea with Mrs. Butler and Ariadne Oliver. Miranda identifies herself as the daughter of Mrs. Butler and the niece of Ariadne Oliver. As they walk through the garden, Miranda describes her habit of observing nature and people from trees. She reveals that the garden was once a quarry where a woman's body was found. Miranda discloses that the victim, Joyce, died by drowning, a fact she learned from overhearing the cook, Mrs. Pelling, and the cleaning lady, Mrs. Mundt, discussing how Joyce's head was dunked in a bucket of water. Miranda explains she was not at the party due to a fever and a sore throat. Miranda then leads Poirot through a hedge and past a cucumber frame to a small bungalow, where she announces she has brought him safely.",
